				\begin{document}$$k_{sum}$$\end{document}ksum in identifying influential nodes depends on yet another factor, the density of the network. The network density is an important factor in network science and also in spreading dynamics. It is a measure of the average degree of the nodes in the network, i.e., the average number of edges incident on a vertex. Changing the density of a network with even a single connected component changes its structural behavior as shown in Fig. 2.

