In an epidemic model, infection probability is an important factor as the real infection rate varies from network to network, depending on the network connectivity, the interest in the topic, and many others. Hence, it is difficult to estimate the real infection rate of a network. In this study, we use the infection probability which is close to the network epidemic threshold12,39. Our experiments show that the ngsc method is robust to different values of the SIR infection probability \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta $$\end{document}β and particularly yields good performance for values just above \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta _{th}$$\end{document}βth where SIR is most valuable.
